BEGIN_PGML Where possible, simplify the following expressions by combining like terms.
END_PGML
############################################################ # Scaffold ############################################################ Scaffold::Begin(numbered => 1,is_open => "correct_or_first_incorrect",can_open => always,);
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML [`6c+12c-5c`]
[@KeyboardInstructions('If it cannot be simplified, just enter it as is.')@]**
[_]{$ans1}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION All three terms are like terms, so they may combined. We combine them two at a time:
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} 6c+12c-5c \amp=(6c+12c)-5c\\ \amp=(6+12)c-5c\\ \amp=18c-5c\\ \amp=(18-5)c=13c \end{aligned} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML [`-5q^2-3q^2`]
[@KeyboardInstructions('If it cannot be simplified, just enter it as is.')@]**
[_]{$ans2}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The terms [`-5q^2`] and [`-3q^2`] are like terms, so we may combine them. Note we are using one of the subtraction versions of the distributive property.
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} -5q^2-3q^2 \amp=(-5-3)q^2\\ \amp=-8q^2 \end{aligned} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML [`x-5y+4x`]
[@KeyboardInstructions('If it cannot be simplified, just enter it as is.')@]**
[_]{$ans3}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The terms [`x`] and [`4x`] are like terms, while the other term is different. Using the associative and commutative properties of addition early in the process allows us to place the two like terms next to each other, and then combine them:
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} x-5y+4x \amp=x+(-5y)+4x\\ \amp=x+((-5y)+4x)\\ \amp=x+(4x+(-5y))\\ \amp=(x+4x)+(-5y)\\ \amp=(1+4)x+(-5y)\\ \amp=5x+(-5y)=5x-5y \end{aligned} ```]
This walkthrough uses the algebra properties cleanly and clearly one step at a time, but if you are combining like terms more quickly, there's nothing at all wrong with that.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
Section::End();
